Can a Machine Think? Or Does It Only Follow Rules?

Have you ever followed a recipe while cooking? If you were a robot cook, and the recipe said, “add two cups of water,” you would do exactly that — even if the food already looked watery. Now compare that to how a human cooks. You taste the food, notice it’s too thin, and adjust. This simple difference shows the heart of today’s question: when a machine does something smart, is it actually thinking, or is it just following instructions very carefully?

Most machines start with rules, which are clear instructions like “if this happens, then do that.” A traffic light is a perfect example. If the timer ends, the light turns red. It doesn’t understand traffic, and it doesn’t care if the road is empty. It simply follows the rules. Computers work in a similar way. They are extremely fast and extremely accurate at following instructions, but following rules is not the same as thinking. Thinking means adjusting when the situation changes in a way you didn’t expect. If a new situation appears that isn’t written in the rules, the machine gets stuck — while a human can usually figure something out.

This is where humans and machines begin to feel different. Humans don’t just follow rules — we learn from experience. If you touch something hot once, you don’t need a rulebook to remind you next time. Your brain remembers the experience and changes your behavior. Machines don’t learn this way naturally. If you only give a machine rules, it will repeat the same mistake again and again unless someone updates those rules. This is why early computers felt rigid and limited, even though they were very powerful.

To make machines act more intelligently, we stopped giving them only rules and started giving them examples. Instead of saying “do this, then that,” we show the machine many situations and let it find patterns on its own. This is similar to how a child learns. You don’t explain every rule of balance before a child rides a bicycle — you let them try, fall, and improve. When machines start improving based on examples and feedback instead of fixed rules, they begin to look less like rule-followers and more like learners. How this works is something we’ll explore in future videos.

So here’s the key idea to remember. Machines don’t think the way humans do, but they also aren’t just simple rule-followers anymore. They sit somewhere in between. They follow instructions, but they can also adjust based on experience. In the next part of this series, we’ll take a closer look at how machines learn from data — a process called machine learning.


